Western Cape Health authorities say the risk of South Africa experiencing a second wave of Covid-19 is high. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Western Cape Health authorities say the risk of South Africa experiencing a second wave of COVID-19 is high. Several countries are already experiencing a second wave. The province is readying itself for this eventuality and South Africans are being urged to be vigilant. Western Cape Head of Health Keith Cloete says the province is being cautious. COVID-19: Expect a second wave of infections - Sama “We are erring on the side of caution. And, therefore our position at the moment is based on international experiences. The risk of having a second wave is significant. It is high and we are preparing as if we will get a second wave,” he said. Cloete says there is a strategy in place.
“To make sure that any sign of small outbreaks needs to be recognized early, contained early so that we can contain it as it happens while being extremely vigilant that we guard against any escalation into size if a second wave”. He says it is still unclear when the second wave will hit. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.